\subsection{Foundational basic-open cover infrastructure (iter-054)}

To instantiate $\HasAffineCechAcyclicCover\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$ (the carrier introduced iter-053) for the structure sheaf, the standard route picks per affine $U$ a \emph{basic-open cover}: given a spanning subset $s \subseteq \Gamma(C, U)$ (i.e. $\mathtt{Ideal.span}\,s = \top$), the family $\mathcal U \,:\, s \to \Opens$, $f \mapsto C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{basicOpen}\,f$, satisfies $\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i = U$ (Mathlib $\mathtt{IsAffineOpen.iSup\_basicOpen\_eq\_self\_iff}$, \texttt{AffineScheme.lean} L898). Each member is itself an affine open (Mathlib $\mathtt{IsAffineOpen.basicOpen}$, L589).

Iter-054 wraps these Mathlib lemmas into the project's conventions (parameterised by $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat.\mathtt{of}\,k))$) so iter-055+ instantiation work for $\HasAffineCechAcyclicCover\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$ can call the constructor + supremum + affine-membership directly. This mirrors iter-047's foundational parameterised Čech infrastructure (4 declarations / +60 LOC) decomposition pattern: package thin Mathlib wrappers as named project-local declarations so the substantive multi-iteration work downstream focuses purely on content (Koszul acyclicity + Čech-vs-derived comparison) rather than re-deriving infrastructure at every call site.

\begin{definition}\leanok
[Basic-open cover from a spanning subset, iter-054]
  \label{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat.\mathtt{of}\,k))$, $U : \Opens\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat}$. Given a subset $s \subseteq \Gamma(C.\mathtt{left}, U)$, the basic-open cover is the family
  \[
    \mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s \,:\, s \to \Opens\,C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{toTopCat}, \qquad f \mapsto C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{basicOpen}\,(f : \Gamma(C.\mathtt{left}, U)).
  \]
  $\mathtt{noncomputable}$ because $\mathtt{Scheme.basicOpen}$ returns data via $\mathtt{presheaf.map}$.
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[Supremum equality for the basic-open cover from generators, iter-054]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_supr_of_span_eq_top}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_supr_of_span_eq_top}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  Under $(h_U : \IsAffineOpen\,U)$ and $(h_s : \mathtt{Ideal.span}\,s = \top)$, the basic-open cover covers $U$ exactly:
  \[
    \bigsqcup_i\,\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s\,i \,=\, U.
  \]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
\leanok
  Direct application of Mathlib's $\mathtt{IsAffineOpen.iSup\_basicOpen\_eq\_self\_iff}$ (\texttt{Mathlib/AlgebraicGeometry/AffineScheme.lean} L898), which states for affine $U$, $\bigsqcup_{f : s} X.\mathtt{basicOpen}\,(f : \Gamma(X, U)) = U \iff \mathtt{Ideal.span}\,s = \top$. Body: $\mathtt{by}\,\mathtt{unfold}\,\mathtt{basicOpenCover};\,\mathtt{exact}\,h_U.\mathtt{iSup\_basicOpen\_eq\_self\_iff.mpr}\,h_s$. The $\mathtt{unfold}$ step is load-bearing — without it, the $s \to \Opens$ shape from $\mathtt{basicOpenCover}$ doesn't directly unify with the iSup form Mathlib's lemma returns. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-054 pass) confirms kernel-only axioms $[\propext, \Classical.\mathtt{choice}, \Quot.\mathtt{sound}]$.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[Each member of the basic-open cover is affine, iter-054]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_isAffineOpen}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_isAffineOpen}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  Under $(h_U : \IsAffineOpen\,U)$ and $(i : s)$, $\IsAffineOpen\,(\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s\,i)$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
\leanok
  Direct application of Mathlib's $\mathtt{IsAffineOpen.basicOpen}$ (\texttt{Mathlib/AlgebraicGeometry/AffineScheme.lean} L589), which states for $h_U : \IsAffineOpen\,U$ and $f : \Gamma(X, U)$, $\IsAffineOpen\,(X.\mathtt{basicOpen}\,f)$. Body: $\mathtt{by}\,\mathtt{unfold}\,\mathtt{basicOpenCover};\,\mathtt{exact}\,h_U.\mathtt{basicOpen}\,i.1$. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-054 pass) confirms kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Toward the iter-055+ comparison theorem (informal scoping)}

Mathlib has $\mathtt{cechComplexFunctor}$ (\texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/Cech.lean}) but \emph{no} comparison theorem to derived-functor cohomology. The substantive iter-055+ obligation is to construct, for any sheaf $F$ on $C.\mathtt{left}$ and cover $\mathcal U$ with $[\IsCechAcyclicCover\,F\,\mathcal U]$ (\emph{or} a slightly weaker hypothesis), a natural $\LinearEquiv$
\[
  \mathrm{compIso}_n \,:\, \cechCohomology\,C\,F\,\mathcal U\,n \;\equiv_k\; \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,\big(\bigsqcup_i \mathcal U_i\big), \qquad \forall n.
\]
The standard mathematical decomposition is the \emph{Cartan-Leray spectral sequence} (Stacks 03OU; Wikipedia ``Čech-to-derived functor spectral sequence''):
\[
  E_2^{p,q} \;=\; \check H^p\big(\mathcal U,\, \underline{H^q}(F)\big) \;\Longrightarrow\; H^{p+q}\big(\bigsqcup\mathcal U,\, F\big),
\]
which under the acyclicity hypothesis $\check H^q(\mathcal U_{i_0..i_p}, F) = 0$ for $q > 0$ collapses on the $E_2$ page to give $\check H^n \cong H^n$. Mathlib does not have the spectral-sequence machinery in the required form; the project-local construction is therefore expected via the dual chain-level Mayer-Vietoris sheaf-resolution route (Stacks 01EO):
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Construct the augmented sheaf-level complex $\mathcal{F}_{\bullet} \,:\, n \mapsto \bigoplus_{i_0 < \cdots < i_n} (j_{i_0\cap\cdots\cap i_n})_! ((\mathtt{presheafToSheaf}).\mathrm{obj}((\mathtt{yoneda} \circ \free\,k).\mathrm{obj}\,\mathcal U_{i_0\cap\cdots\cap i_n}))$ with augmentation to $(\mathtt{presheafToSheaf}).\mathrm{obj}((\mathtt{yoneda}\circ\free\,k).\mathrm{obj}\,(\bigsqcup\mathcal U))$ (sheafified Mayer-Vietoris resolution of the free sheaf on $\bigsqcup\mathcal U$). Show this complex is exact in positive degrees under acyclicity (the substantive computational step; alternating-face complex is exact, equivalently the local-section complex on each $\mathcal U_{i_0..i_p}$ is the Koszul complex of localisations exact under unit-ideal hypothesis).
  \item Apply $\Hom(-, F)$ degree-wise, picking up $\Hom(\mathcal{F}_n, F) \cong \prod_{i_0,\ldots,i_n} F(\mathcal U_{i_0\cap\cdots\cap i_n}) = (\cechCochain)_n$ on the LHS, and $\Hom\big((\mathtt{presheafToSheaf}).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathtt{yoneda}\circ\free\,k).\mathrm{obj}\,(\bigsqcup\mathcal U),\, F\big) = \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,(\bigsqcup\mathcal U)$ on the RHS at degree 0.
  \item Pass to cohomology and chain to $\Ext^n$ via the augmentation; under acyclicity the augmentation is a quasi-iso, and the induced map on $\Ext^n$ gives the comparison.
\end{enumerate}
This decomposes into multiple iterations:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{iter-055 (basic-open Koszul acyclicity)}: prove $\IsCechAcyclicCover\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,(\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s)$ for spanning $s$. The Čech complex on basic opens of an affine $\Spec\,A$ evaluates to the alternating-sum complex on localisations $n \mapsto \bigoplus_{i_0..i_n \in s} M_{f_{i_0..i_n}}$ for $M$ the $\Gamma(C, U)$-module structure of $(\toModuleKSheaf\,C).\mathrm{obj}\,U$, exact when $f_i$ generate the unit ideal. References: Hartshorne III.3.5, Stacks 02FQ, Eisenbud Commutative Algebra §17 Koszul resolution. Estimate: 2--4 iterations, $\sim 150$--$250$ LOC.
  \item \textbf{iter-056+ (Čech-vs-derived comparison)}: construct the sheaf-level Mayer-Vietoris resolution and chain via $\Ext$ functoriality. Estimate: 4--6 iterations, $\sim 200$--$400$ LOC. Package result as $\HasCechToHModuleIso\,F\,\mathcal U$ instance via $\langle\langle\mathtt{the\_iso}\rangle\rangle$.
  \item \textbf{iter-057+ (packaging)}: bundle iter-055 + iter-056+ into a single $\HasAffineCechAcyclicCover\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)$ instance using iter-054's $\mathtt{basicOpenCover}$, $\mathtt{basicOpenCover\_supr\_of\_span\_eq\_top}$, $\mathtt{basicOpenCover\_isAffineOpen}$. Iter-053 producer fires automatically.
\end{itemize}
